But whereas in the Iliad they are scenes of the occupa- tions of everyday life, in the Aeneid they are drawn from Roman history. In one the Capitol is saved from the Gauls by the warning of the sacred geese.

ἱ In another we see the crowning victory of Actium,

where the fleet of Augustus and the forces of law and order, crushed the navies of Antony and Cleopatra, and Italian civilization triumphed over the pomp and licence of the East. It is passages such as these which more than anything else make the Aeneid something more than a mere story. But the national purpose runs through every book of the Aeneid, and is emphasized by a thousand subtle toucheS. All lovers of poetry will find much in the Aeneid to delight them by sheer beauty. But unless the whole purpose of the poem be borne steadily in view, they run the risk of missing many of its beauties and fail- ing to appreciate much of its true greatness The Aeneid is not only one of the most beautiful of poems; it is also the one true epic of a nation’s great· ness that the world has seen or is ever likely to see.

H. E. BUTLER.
